<TITLE> Anti-graft drive to continue, says Masud </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 30 (bdnews24.com)- Coordinator of the National Coordination Committee for Checking Corruption, Lieutenant General Masud Uddin Chowdhury Saturday said that checking corruption was a big challenge for Bangladesh. The challenge would have to be faced by creating public opinion against corruption through adopting transparency and accountability, he added. "Though those involved in corruption are frightened, this drive enjoys massive public support," he told a seminar on 'Checking Corruption: Sharing Experience," as the special guest at the National Press Club. Describing the post January 11 situation he said, "Our drive against corruption will continue. All of us will have to work together to build a corruption-free environment." He urged all to build a social movement against corruption alongside the government programme. He said, "Let our slogan be 'Love the country, hate corruption." On widespread corruption at all levels of society, Masud said, "We must change the situation. We must ensure representation of honest and efficient people in the Jatiya Sangsad. He stressed the role of the mass media in building public opinion against corruption. He urged the civil society to come forward to check corruption. In his written speech, Masud explained the aim and activities of the National Coordination Committee for Checking Corruption. Pakistani columnist Ikram Sehgal who was the main speaker at the seminar described the anti-corruption drive in Pakistan. Retired major SM Ibrahim, economist Prof Mahbubullah, Dr Hossain Zillur Rahman and Prof Shamsher Ali also spoke. bdnew
